The Arroyo is a dry canyon in the eastern desert, carved by a branch of the Iseth watershed that no longer carries stable surface flow. It connects to the Deepwell Confluence basin. Seasonal floodwater once ran through it; drought cycles killed the river permanently. The critical transformation was institutional, not geological: the Arroyo became a place where water volume was translated into legal obligation. Five historical layers remain simultaneously active. Keeper era: thirst oaths (temporary legal declarations allowing emergency water draws in exchange for deferred service or levy), silt tallies (volumetric notations forecasting transport viability), witness stones (paired marker tablets recording both route distance and owed cistern allocation). Salt Ledger era: toll courts carved into cutbanks and ruin terraces, confiscation vaults for undeclared goods, mortuary intake rooms for those who died "in arrears" — the phrase "unpaid names" originates here, referring to dead travelers whose funerary rites were withheld pending debt settlement. Pyramid influence: Moon-descending legal language reframing debt default as spiritual trespass, producing palimpsest inscriptions (Keeper numerics under Ledger seals, Ledger seals under Moon clauses, Moon clauses crossed by preservation annotations). Collapse period: Jackal-derived synod offshoots simplified legal formulas into coercive toll liturgy; "authorized thirst" became both prayer and threat; scorpion colony expansion through unattended mortuary sectors and seep-warm hollows. Modern control: Charter Reclaimers (synod-descended militants running extortion checkpoints with copied charter rods and counterfeit witness seals), Dustbound Court-Dead (undead former assessors reenacting procedure fragments), Brood of the Resin Matriarch (canyon-adapted mega-scorpion lineage in ossuary-to-seep-rock interface zones), and Fault Manifestations (elemental forms rising from meridian-scar fractures).

