From Midgaard's registry perspective, the Arroyo is evidence of what happens when documentation infrastructure collapses: law persists as ritual, ritual decays into extortion, inscriptions become competing claims no authority can adjudicate. The palimpsest inscriptions — Keeper numerics under Ledger seals under Moon clauses — parallel Midgaard's contested archives: each regime rewrote prior authority without destroying the prior text. The Charter Reclaimers — carrying copied charter rods and counterfeit witness seals, claiming to "enforce ancient passage law" — are the endpoint when authentic authority lapses and counterfeit authority fills the vacuum. Midgaard's Lantern Registry, Guard Command patrols, and Ledgerhouse maintenance are mechanisms for keeping authentic authority distinguishable from counterfeits. The Reckoning faction cites the Arroyo as evidence of what sealed archives become after institutional failure: palimpsest claims every faction reads as legitimating their incompatible project.

